description:
Follow up issue on https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/merge_requests/93283#note_1045051673

Should there be a standard way to return errors in mutations. In some places we return `null` in the fields available on the mutation, if the mutation has errors. In others, we allow to query the unchanged object as part of the response of the mutation.

## Initial discussion
Do we have this as the standard way to handle errors? Perhaps @gitlab-org/graphql-experts can chime in? I don't see anything in the GraphQL spec about this, other than something that might apply? Of course this is talking about top level errors
```
If an error was encountered during the execution that prevented a valid response, the data entry in the response should be null
```
Also from the `graphql` ruby gem we have [this](https://graphql-ruby.org/mutations/mutation_errors#nullable-mutation-payload-fields).

Unless there's a better reason I'm not seeing, perhaps it's better to return null? We might save some DB queries, reduce the response size and also, we could expect that the frontend has a saved state of the object before calling the mutation, right? So, why fetch it unchanged from a failed mutation?

## Example mutation
```graphql
mutation {
  issueSetConfidential(input: iid: "2", projectPath: "flightjs/Flight", confidential: true) {
    issue {
      id
      confidential
    }
    errors
  }
}
```

### Response with original object unchanged
```json
[
  {
    "data": {
      "issueSetConfidential": {
        "issue": {
          "id": "gid://gitlab/Issue/42",
          "confidential": false,
        },
        "errors": [
          "Confidential confidential parent can not be used if there are not-confidential children."
        ],
      }
    }
  }
]

```

### Response with null `issue` if the mutation contains errors
```json
[
  {
    "data": {
      "issueSetConfidential": {
        "issue": null,
        "errors": [
          "Confidential confidential parent can not be used if there are not-confidential children."
        ],
      }
    }
  }
]

```

